I want to open HTML in Firefox but Firefox is not my default browser. So in python webbrowser will not open firefox. How can I do this with firefox?

ASSISTANT:
You can force Python to open Firefox even if it isn’t your system default. The easiest way is to register Firefox with the webbrowser module (pointing to Firefox’s executable) and then open the URL with that browser. You can also use a direct subprocess call if you prefer.

Option 1: Using Python's webbrowser (cross-platform)
- What it does: registers Firefox with its executable path and then opens the URL in Firefox.

Example (adjust paths for your OS):

- Windows (typical paths; may be in Program Files or Program Files (x86)):
  import sys
  import webbrowser

  url = "https://example.com"

  # Path to Firefox executable (adjust if needed)
  firefox_path = r"C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\firefox.exe"

  webbrowser.register('firefox', None, webbrowser.BackgroundBrowser(firefox_path))
  webbrowser.get('firefox').open(url, new=2)

- macOS:
  firefox_path = "/Applications/Firefox.app/Contents/MacOS/firefox"
  webbrowser.register('firefox', None, webbrowser.BackgroundBrowser(firefox_path))
  webbrowser.get('firefox').open(url, new=2)

- Linux (Firefox in PATH):
  firefox_path = "/usr/bin/firefox"  # or just "firefox" if it's in PATH
  webbrowser.register('firefox', None, webbrowser.BackgroundBrowser(firefox_path))
  webbrowser.get('firefox').open(url, new=2)

If you’re opening a local HTML file, convert it to a file URL first:

from pathlib import Path
url = Path("/path/to/file.html").resolve().as_uri()  # e.g., file:///home/user/file.html
webbrowser.get('firefox').open(url, new=2)

Option 2: Open Firefox directly (bypass webbrowser)
If you just want a guaranteed Firefox launch and don’t mind using subprocess, you can call Firefox directly:

- Windows:
  import subprocess
  subprocess.Popen([r"C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\firefox.exe", "https://example.com"])

- macOS:
  subprocess.Popen(["/Applications/Firefox.app/Contents/MacOS/firefox", "https://example.com"])

- Linux:
  subprocess.Popen(["firefox", "https://example.com"])  # Firefox in PATH

For a local file:
  subprocess.Popen([firefox_path, Path("/path/to/file.html").resolve().as_uri()])

Notes and tips
- If you get a “not found” error, double-check Firefox’s install path. On Windows you might also have it in "C:\Program Files (x86)\Mozilla Firefox\firefox.exe".
- The new=2 argument in webbrowser.open prompts Firefox to open a new tab when possible.
- If Firefox isn’t installed, these methods will fail—install Firefox first or handle the exception gracefully.
- If you prefer, you can also set Firefox as your default browser system-wide; this approach just lets your Python script explicitly use Firefox without changing defaults.

